@node "INTRODUCTION" "Introduction"
Online-o-Meter: What is it?

Online-o-Meter is a tool to help you keep track of your phone bill
when using a modem.

Once configured with your phone-company's charge data it sits in the
background, counts the duration of your call and calculates the cost.
All you have to do is tell it where you are calling, when the call
starts, and when it ends.  Using ARexx, you can get your
Communications software to do this for you automatically.
Online-o-Meter works out what the current charges are for itself, and
takes account of all the pit-falls and tar-traps which normally make
it so difficult to calculate charges correctly, such as Minimum
Charges and Time and Cost rounding.

All this means that by the time your phone-bill arrives, you'll have
saved up your pennies in sufficient quantity, or at least braced
yourself for the shock!

@endnode

@node "REQUIREMENTS" "Requirements"
What you need to use it

Online-o-Meter has been designed to provide the maximum functionality
for the minimum use of of resources. Its separate Preferences Editor
and duel threaded operation mean that memory and CPU usage are kept as
low as possible, without sacrificing usefulness.

All that is really required is an Amiga with version 2.04 or higher of
the operating system. No non-standard libraries are required.

@endnode

@node "INSTALLATION" "Installation"
Where do I put everything?

There are two main parts to install, the Preferences Editor, @{"OnlinePrefs" link "ONLINEPREFS" 0} 
and the Meter itself, @{"OnlineMeter" link "ONLINEMETER" 0}. 
Location of the two parts is not important. I suggest that OnlinePrefs 
be copied to SYS:Prefs and OnlineMeter to SYS:Utilities or SYS:Tools, 
but that is entirely up to you (mine's in AmiTCP:bin).

OnlineMeter requires an IFF preference file generated by OnlinePrefs. 
By default this is stored in the ENVARC:Online and ENV:Online drawers as
Online.prefs. A @{"ToolType or Argument" link ONLINEMETER_ARG_PREFSFILE} given to OnlineMeter, or a 
command given to OnlineMeter via @{"ARexx" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_READPREFS" 0} can load the file from elsewhere.

@endnode

@node "TERMINOLOGY" "Online-o-Meter Terminology"
What it all means...

Before we jump into all the details, I need to explain some
terminology which is used to describe the the Charges database
Online-o-Meter uses to calculate call costs.


The primary factor effecting the cost of a call is, of course, the
destination. In Online terms, we call this a @{b}Zone@{ub}. Typical Zones 
would be for Local calls, National and International calls. The Zone itself
has three important pieces of information associated with it: the
@{"Minimum Charge" link "TERMINOLOGY_MINIMUM_CHARGE"} the @{"Time Rounding" link "TERMINOLOGY_TIME_ROUNDING"} factor and the @{"Cost Rounding" link "TERMINOLOGY_COST_ROUNDING"} factor.


Each Zone has a set of @{b}Time Bands@{ub} associated with it, these
are the tariffs for each Zone e.g. Peak, Standard and Economy, and
control the cost per time unit of a call at a particular time. Time
Bands have two pieces of information associated with them: the Band
@{b}Day Range@{ub}, which gives the range of days over which the Time
Band is applicable, and the @{b}Cost per Minute@{ub} of calls made in
the Band, which is used to derive the actual cost of the call.


Finally, each Time Band has a set of @{b}Band Times@{ub} which govern
at what times in the Day Range a particular Time Band is in effect.


O.K., that's enough terminology to be getting on with... for now!

@endnode

@node "TERMINOLOGY_MINIMUM_CHARGE" "Zone Minimum Charge"
Minimum Charge

The Minimum Charge is the lowest possible cost of a call to a Zone. It
is levied the moment that the destination picks up the call. Once
levied the cost of the call remains at this level until the duration
cost outweighs it.

To put this more clearly, if the Minimum charge were 10 pence, and
each unit cost 5p and lasted a minute, then the call would cost just
10 pence until the call lasted over 2 minutes.

Minimum Charge is replaced by @{"Unit" link "TERMINOLOGY_UNIT"} Cost
when operating in Unit mode.

@endnode

@node "TERMINOLOGY_TIME_ROUNDING" "Zone Time Rounding"
Time Rounding

This is the time unit which your phone company uses to calculate its
bills.  Typically this is either by the minute or the second.

For example, if your phone company charges by the minute and you make
a call of 1 minute 1 second, you would pay for 2 minutes of call,
whereas if they charged by the second you would only pay for 61
seconds.

When in @{"Unit" link "TERMINOLOGY_UNIT"} mode all calls are rounded to
the nearest Unit of time.

@endnode

@node "TERMINOLOGY_COST_ROUNDING" "Zone Cost Rounding"
Cost Rounding

This is the cost unit that your phone company rounds your bills to.
Note that they always round up (i.e. ceiling operation).

Usually charges per unit time will include a fraction, e.g. 4.68
pence, so the cost of a call will depend on the accuracy to which your
bill is rounded. For example if you make a call of 5 minutes at 4.68
pence per minute and your phone company rounds to the nearest 1 pence
then it will cost you 24 pence (23.4 rounded up to the nearest penny),
if they charge to the nearest 0.1 of a penny then it would cost you
only 23.4 pence, which can make a lot of difference over a quarterly
bill (I clocked up over 1000 minutes last quarter, so my bill would
differ by 600 pence (Ł6.00) over this period).

When in @{"Unit" link "TERMINOLOGY_UNIT"} mode all calls are rounded to the
nearest Unit price.

@endnode

@node "TERMINOLOGY_UNIT" "Units"
Units

Some phone companies calculate not directly by the cost of a
particular unit of time, but by establishing a price per Unit, and
then calculating the number of seconds for which that Unit lasts.

For example, the Unit cost might be 4.2p, this is applicable to any
destination, but how long the Unit lasts is dependant on the
destination and time of calling. At Standard rates a Unit might last
32 seconds when calling Nationally, but 220 seconds when making a
local call.

This is all needlessly complicated but Online-o-Meter takes care of it
all: all you have to do is type in the Unit cost and the Seconds per
Unit for various Times and Zones and it will do the rest...

@endnode

@node "PROGRAMS" "OnlineMeter and OnlinePrefs"

Online-o-Meter's functionality is spilt into two separate executables
for the sake of efficiency and practicality:

@{"OnlineMeter" link "ONLINEMETER"} is the actual tool used to calculate your phone
bills. It provides a window with basic controls and an @{"ARexx" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX"} port for
automatic interation. It reads a configuration file containing the
charging information.

@{"OnlinePrefs" link "ONLINEPREFS"} is used to contruct Zones, TimeBands and
BandTimes, and also control the default settings which effect
OnlineMeter's behaviour. It saves them out to an IFF file for
OnlineMeter to read and use to calculate the bills.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS" "OnlinePrefs - Online-o-Meter Preferences Editor"

@{b}OnlinePrefs@{ub} is started from the Workbench by double clicking on its
icon, and from the CLI by typing its name. It can take several
@{"Arguments" link "ONLINEPREFS_STARTUP"} which are explained later, but it its `bare' state it
firstly looks for a file called Online.prefs in either the ENV:Online/
or ENVARC:Online/ directories. If this file is found then the
information in it is read and presented for editing in the OnlinePrefs
window. If the file is not found then a default preferences instance
is created in memory and presented for modification.

Preferences consist of @{"Billing" link "ONLINEPREFS_ZONES"} and @{"Operational" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALSETTINGS"} Information.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_STARTUP" "OnlinePrefs Startup Arguments"

OnlinePrefs supports several arguments via either Icon ToolTypes or
CLI Arguments. The keywords are the same in either case and they
follow standard (i.e. Style Guide compliant) Amiga conventions:

SYNOPSIS

   OnlinePrefs
      @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"} (CLI Arg only),
      @{"ACTION" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_ACTION"} (ToolType only)
      @{"USE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_USE"}/S,
      @{"SAVE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_SAVE"}/S,
      @{"EDIT" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_EDIT"}/S,
      @{"CREATEICONS" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_CREATEICONS"}/S,
      @{"PUBSCREEN" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_PUBSCREEN"}/K


If OnlinePrefs is started by Double-Clicking or Multiple-Selecting a
Preferences file icon then the file will be loaded into OnlinePrefs
instead of the default settings.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM" "FROM"

SYNOPSIS

   CLI Argument  -  FROM <preferences filename>

FUNCTION

   Causes OnlinePrefs to load the given configuration file. By default, and
   with the @{"EDIT" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_EDIT"} argument the OnlinePrefs window will then open for editing. 
   When used with the @{"USE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_USE"} and @{"SAVE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_SAVE"} arguments this file is used 
   as the basis for their operations.

SEE ALSO

   @{"ACTION" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_ACTION"}
   @{"USE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_USE"}
   @{"SAVE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_SAVE"}
   @{"EDIT" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_EDIT"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_ACTION" "ACTION"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  -  ACTION=<USE or SAVE or EDIT>

FUNCTION

   When given in an OnlineMeter Preferences file icon causes the given 
   action to be performed after OnlinePrefs has loaded the Preferences 
   file.

   It has no effect in the OnlinePrefs Tool icon.

SEE ALSO

   @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"}
   @{"USE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_USE"}
   @{"SAVE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_SAVE"}
   @{"EDIT" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_EDIT"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_USE" "USE"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  USE (or ACTION=USE in Prefs File)
   CLI Argument  -  USE

FUNCTION

   When used in conjunction with @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"} OnlinePrefs loads the specified
   configuration file and saves it to ENV:Online/Online.prefs thus causing
   OnlineMeter to re-load and use this set of preferences for the current
   session.

SEE ALSO

   @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"}
   @{"ACTION" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_ACTION"}
   @{"SAVE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_SAVE"}
   @{"EDIT" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_EDIT"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_SAVE" "SAVE"

SYNOPSIS

  WB ToolType   -  SAVE (or ACTION=SAVE in Prefs File)
  CLI Argument  -  SAVE

FUNCTION 

   When used in conjunction with @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"} OnlinePrefs loads the specified
   configuration file and saves it to both ENV:Online/Online.prefs and 
   ENVARC:Online/Online.prefs thus causing OnlineMeter to re-load and use
   this set of preferences, and to use them for future sessions after a 
   re-boot.

SEE ALSO

   @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"}
   @{"ACTION" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_ACTION"}
   @{"USE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_USE"}
   @{"EDIT" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_EDIT"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_EDIT" "EDIT"

SYNOPSIS

  WB ToolType  -  EDIT (or ACTION=EDIT in Prefs File)
  CLI Argument -  EDIT

FUNCTION

   This is the default option for OnlinePrefs: the configuration file will
   be read and presented for edit. When used with @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"} the given file 
   will be loaded, otherwise ENV:Online/Online.prefs will be loaded.

SEE ALSO

   @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"}
   @{"ACTION" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_ACTION"}
   @{"USE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_USE"}
   @{"SAVE" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_SAVE"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_CREATEICONS" "CREATEICONS"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  CREATEICONS=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument  -  CREATEICONS or NOCREATEICONS

FUNCTION

   By default OnlinePrefs creates icons for preference files it saves 
   via the menus (i.e. not by the @{"Save or Use" link "ONLINEPREFS_SETTINGPREFS"} buttons).

   Specifying CREATEICONS=NO (WB) or NOCREATEICONS (CLI) turns this 
   feature off.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_PUBSCREEN" "PUBSCREEN"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  PUBSCREEN=<public screen name>
   CLI Argument  -  PUBSCREEN <public screen name>

FUNCTION

   By default OnlinePrefs opens on the Default Public Screen, which is 
   usually the Workbench Screen. Using this argument OnlinePrefs can be
   made to open its window on another Public Screen.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALSETTINGS" "Global Settings"

Top-Level Preferences

OnlineMeter's default global (rather than Zone orientated) behavior
can be controlled by options set from OnlinePrefs. 

Facilities offered are grouped into three categories:

@{b}Window@{ub}

	@{"Initial Window Size" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_OPENSMALL"}

	@{"Initial Window State" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_OPENHIDDEN"}

	@{"Public Screen for Display" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_PUBSCREEN"}

@{b}Logging@{ub}

	@{"Call Logging Enabled/Disabled" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOG"}

	@{"Accumulated Call Totals Logging" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_VARS"}

	@{"Call Logging File" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOGFILE"}

@{b}Meter@{ub}

	@{"Commodities Hotkeys" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_HOTKEYS"}

	@{"ARexx Port Name" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_REXXNAME"}

	@{"Accumulative Display On/Off" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_ACCUMULATIVE"}

	@{"End of Time Band Warning On/Off" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_WARN"}

	@{"End of Time Band Warning Beep On/Off" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_BEEP"}
	
@endnode



@rem **** Window ****

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_OPENSMALL" "Open Small Attribute"

The @{i}Small@{ui} checkbox controls the initial size of the
OnlineMeter window. The window can either be `Big', displaying the
current Zone and call Cost and Duration with Control Gadgets, or
`Small' where the window shrinks to a small screen titlebar
alternating between showing the Cost and Duration.

Checking the Small checkbox causes OnlineMeter to open a small
window.

SEE ALSO

   @{"SMALL" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_SMALL"}
   @{"Display" link "ONLINEMETER_DISPLAY"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_OPENHIDDEN" "Open Hidden Attribute"

The @{i}Hidden@{ui} checkbox controls whether OnlineMeter opens its
window immediately on startup, or waits until it is specifically told
to Show itself via a Hotkey, a Commodities Exchange program or an
ARexx command.

While OnlineMeter is Hidden all operations not requiring the GUI can
take place, using the Commodities and ARexx interfaces instead. In
fact OnlineMeter may operate completely without ever opening its
window, using the other interfaces to tell it to exit.

Checking the Hidden checkbox causes OnlineMeter to start up without
opening its window.

SEE ALSO
   @{"HIDDEN" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_HIDDEN"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_PUBSCREEN" "Public Screen Attribute"

Using the @{i}Screen@{ui} string gadget the name of the Public Screen
that OnlineMeter should open on can be given. 

If the gadget is blank or the screen does not exist then OnlineMeter
will fall back to the Default Public screen, which is usually the
Workbench screen unless this has been changed by a Public Screen
management utility.

SEE ALSO 

   @{"OnlineMeter Argument PUBSCREEN" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_PUBSCREEN"}

@endnode

@rem **** Logging ****

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOG" "Log Attribute"

The Log @{i}Enabled@{ui} checkbox controls whether Call Logging is
turned On or Off. If it is checked then every time a call ends an
entry will be made in a Log File listing the details of the call e.g.
Duration and Cost. If the @{"Vars" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_VARS"} checkbox is also checked then on exit
OnlineMeter will add the accumulated cost of all calls made in the
session to the environmental variables @{"ONLINEDURATION" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG_VARS"} and 
@{"ONLINECOST" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG_VARS"}.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Log File Attribute" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOGFILE"}
   @{"Log Vars Attribute" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_VARS"}
   @{"LOGFILE" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOGFILE"}
   @{"VARS" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_VARS"}
   @{"Log Menu" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_LOG"}
   @{"Logging Calls" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}
   @{"OnlineMeter Log Environmental Variables" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG_VARS"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOGFILE" "Log File Attribute"

The Log string gadget is used to enter the filename of the file to use
for OnlineMeter call information.

If the string is left blank then the default file of "PROGDIR:Online.log" 
will be used, i.e. the log file will be saved in the same directory as
the OnlineMeter program is stored.

The logging information is only saved if Call Logging is enabled.

SEE ALSO

   @{"LOGFILE" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOGFILE"}
   @{"Log Attribute" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOG"}
   @{"Logging Calls" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_VARS" "Log Vars Attribute"

The Log @{i}Vars@{ui} checkbox is used to control saving of
Accumulated call information to Environmental variables. 

If this gadget is checked, and Logging is Enabled, then when
OnlineMeter is exited it adds the total accumulated Cost and Duration
of all calls made while OnlineMeter has been running to the
environmental variables ONLINECOST and ONLINEDURATION, in both ENV:
and ENVARC:, thus maintaining them over reboots.

SEE ALSO
   @{"VARS" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_VARS"}
   @{"OnlineMeter Log Environmental Variables" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG_VARS"}
   @{"LOG" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOG"} 
   @{"Log Menu" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_LOG"}

@endnode

@rem **** Meter ****

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_REXXNAME" "ARexx Port Name Attribute"

Using the @{i}ARexx Port@{ui} string gadget the base name of the ARexx
Port which OnlineMeter will open to accept commands on can be
specified.

The first instance of OnlineMeter will use this name for its port, any
subsequent and simultaneous instances will use this name plus a
numerical extension, e.g. if Rexx Name is "MyOnlineREXX" then the
2nd port will be "MyOnlineREXX.1" and the 5th "MyOnlineRexx.4".

If the string is left blank then the name "OnlineREXX" will be used.


Note that when using ARexx to interact with Online-o-Meter you will need
to quote the port name if it is a mixture of cases to stop ARexx converting
it to upper case. e.g. @{i}address 'OnlineREXX' start@{ui}


SEE ALSO

   @{"REXXNAME" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_REXXNAME"} 
   @{"External Control through ARexx" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_ACCUMULATIVE" "Accumulative Attribute"

The @{i}Accumulative@{ui} checkbox controls how OnlineMeter displays
the Cost and Duration information.

When Accumulative is not checked OnlineMeter displays only the cost
and duration of the @{b}current@{ub} call, or the last call if OnlineMeter 
is Stopped. 

When Accumulative is checked OnlineMeter displays the @{b}total@{ub} duration
and cost of all calls made since startup, including the current one.

Note that this attribute only effects the display of call information:
whatever the state of the checkbox OnlineMeter maintains both
Accumulated and Current call data for use in logging operations.

SEE ALSO
   
   @{"ACCUMULATIVE" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ACCUMULATIVE"}
   @{"Accumulative Menu" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ACCUMULATIVE"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_WARN" "Warn Attribute"

The @{i}Warn@{ui} checkbox controls whether or not OnlineMeter
displays a warning just before the end of the current band. 

If the checkbox is checked then a requester is displayed 3 minutes
before the current band ends, warning the user that prices are about
to change and displaying some information on the current and next band
charges.

SEE ALSO

   @{"WARN" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_WARN"}
   @{"Warn Menu" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_WARNING"}
   @{"Beep Attribute" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_BEEP"}
   @{"BEEPONWARN" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_BEEPONWARN"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_BEEP" "Beep Attribute"

The @{i}Beep@{ui} checkbox controls whether or not OnlineMeter does a
DisplayBeep when the Band Warning appears.

If you are away from the machine, or otherwise not concentrating when
a Band Warning requester appears, and you'd rather not miss it,
checking this gadget makes OnlineMeter flash the display and/or make a
sound (depending on your OS and Preferences) to alert you to the
situation. It has no effect when Band End Warnings are not enabled.

SEE ALSO
   @{"Warn Attribute" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_WARN"}
   @{"BEEPONWARN" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_BEEPONWARN"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_HOTKEYS" "Hotkeys Attributes"

The Cycle gadget immediately to the right of the Meter label
controls which HotKey is being edited in the Hotkey String Gadget to its
right. The Cycle has the values "Show", "Start", "Stop", and "Abort".

The String gadget must contain standard Commodities description
strings, you can find a description of these in your Workbench manual,
or @{"here" link "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS"}.

SEE ALSO

   @{"OnlineMeter Hotkeys" link "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS"}
   @{"OnlineMeter Arguments" link "ONLINEMETER_STARTUP"}

@endnode




@node "ONLINEPREFS_ZONES" "Zones -- the Basis of Billing"

@{b}Zones@{ub}

The principle attribute for billing information is the @{"Zone" link "TERMINOLOGY" 7}. Zones are the
root of all other billing information in OnlineMeter and are created using 
the @{i}Zone@{ui} list and associated gadgets:

@{i}Add @{ui}Creates a new Zone, inserts an initial name of "«new»" into 
the Zone list and selects the Zone name string gadget ready for
editing. See @{"Zone Attributes" link "ONLINEPREFS_ZONE_ATTRIBUTES"} for more information.

@{i}Del @{ui}deletes the currently selected Zone. Note that all
information is destroyed and there is no way to get it back with out
re-loading the preferences file by Cancelling and restarting or
loading from the @{"Project/Open..." link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_OPEN"} Menu.

@{i}U @{ui}and @{i}D @{ui}re-order the currently selected entry in the
list: U moves the entry Up and D moves it Down. This is a purely
asthetic facility, unless you have more than 32 Zones, in which case
you may wish to move the most used Zones to the top of the list so
that they appear in the OnlineMeter @{"Menu" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ZONE_LIST"}.

Attached to each Zone is a list of @{"Time Bands" link "ONLINEPREFS_TIMEBANDS"} which control the cost
of calls made in the Zone.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_ZONE_ATTRIBUTES" "Zone Attributes"

Zone names can be up to 20 characters long and should be unique if you
want to use @{"ARexx" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX"}. Any number of Zones can be entered but no
more than 32 can be displayed in OnlineMeter's @{"Menu" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ZONE_LIST"}. 

Each Zone created has associated with it a @{"Minimum Charge" link "TERMINOLOGY_MINIMUM_CHARGE"}, 
@{"Time Rounding" link "TERMINOLOGY_TIME_ROUNDING"} factor and a @{"Cost Rounding" link "TERMINOLOGY_COST_ROUNDING"} factor. 

Minimum Charge is entered in the @{i}Min Charge@{ui} string gadget and
should be a floating point value with up to 2 decimal places. Normally
this is entered so that the integer part of the number (i.e. the part
before the `.') represents the smallest part of your currency, e.g.
pence (p) in the U.K. and Cents (˘) in the U.S.A. Of course, what you
actually enter in here is up to you (it's a free world, or so we are
brain-washed into believing! C:v] ). For example, if the minimum charge
was 4.68p then one would enter 4.68 into the gadget.

In @{"Unit" link "TERMINOLOGY_UNIT"} mode the Minimum Charge gadget becomes the Unit Cost gadget.


Time Rounding is controlled by the @{i}Time Rounding@{ui} cycle
gadget.  Possible values are @{i}Second@{ui}, @{i}Minute@{ui},
@{i}0.1s@{ui} (tenth of a second) and @{i}0.01s@{ui}. A fifth value
allows selection of @{"Unit" link "TERMINOLOGY_UNIT"} mode where time
(and therefore cost) is rounded to the nearest unit price.


Cost Rounding is controlled by the @{i}Cost Rounding@{ui} cycle gadget.  
Possible values are @{i}0.01@{ui}, @{i}0.10@{ui} and @{i}1.00@{ui}. The units
are the same as those of the Minimum Cost and @{"Cost/Min" link "ONLINEPREFS_TIMEBAND_ATTRIBUTES" 14} gadgets.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_TIMEBANDS" "Time Bands"

@{b}Time Bands@{ub}

@{"Time Bands" link "TERMINOLOGY" 14} form the part of the information OnlineMeter uses to decide
the cost of a call. They are added to the currently selected Zone
using the @{i}Time Band @{ui}list and associated gadgets:

@{i}Add @{ui}Creates a new Time Band, inserts an intial name of
"«new»" into the Time Band list and selects the Time Band name string
gadget ready for editing. See @{"Time Band Attributes" link "ONLINEPREFS_TIMEBAND_ATTRIBUTES"} for more information.

@{i}Del @{ui}deletes the currently selected Time Band. Note that all
Time Band and @{"Band Times" link "ONLINEPREFS_BANDTIMES"} information is destroyed and there is no way 
to get it back with out re-loading the preferences file by Cancelling and 
restarting or loading from the @{"Project/Open..." link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_OPEN"} Menu.

@{i}U @{ui} and @{i}D @{ui}re-order the currently selected entry in
the list.

Attatched to each Time Band is a list of @{"Band Times" link "ONLINEPREFS_BANDTIMES"} which specify at
which times the Time Band is active.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_TIMEBAND_ATTRIBUTES" "Time Band Attributes"

The @{i}From@{ui} and @{i}To@{ui} cycle gadgets control the range of
days over which the currently selected Time Band is active. 

The range is inclusive, and effectively includes the time between
midnight on the From day to one second before midnight on the To day,
e.g. a Weekend band from Sat to Sun lasts from 00:00:00 Saturday
morning to 23:59:59 Sunday night. If you want a band to last just one
day, enter the same day for both From and To. If you want a band to
last all week enter the days in reverse order, e.g. Sun to Sat.

The actual times the Band is active on the days included in the range
is controlled by the @{"Band Times" link "ONLINEPREFS_BANDTIMES"} settings.


The @{i}Cost/Min@{ui} string gadget sets the total cost of each
minute of time when the Time Band is active. This is divided into
quantums of cost using the @{"Zone Time Rounding" link "ONLINEPREFS_ZONE_ATTRIBUTES" 18} setting, and 
then used to calculate the current cost of a call. e.g. if Cost/Min was 6p
and Zone Time Rounding was Second, then a quantum of time would be 0.1p and
this would be added to the cost every Second.

In @{"Unit" link "TERMINOLOGY_UNIT"} mode the @{i}Secs/Unit@{ui} gadget appears in place of
the Cost/Min gadget and is used to enter the number of seconds that a unit
lasts in a particular TimeBand. Every time this amount of time passes the 
@{i}Unit Cost@{ui} amount is added to the cost and a new unit is started. In
this mode a whole unit is added to the cost of the call as soon as it is
started, and the next unit added after Secs/Unit has expired.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_BANDTIMES" "Band Times"

@{b}Band Times@{ub}

@{"Band Times" link "TERMINOLOGY" 19} specify when in the range of @{"Time Band" link "ONLINEPREFS_TIMEBANDS"} days a Time Band is
active. 

@{i}Add @{ui}creates a new Band Time entry in the list, initializing
the time range entry to be from Midnight to (effectively) Midnight
minus one second. See @{"Band Times Attributes" link "ONLINEPREFS_BANDTIMES_ATTRIBUTES"} for details.

@{i}Del @{ui}deletes the currently selected Band Times range. Note
that there is no way to get the information back.

@{i}U @{ui} and @{i}D @{ui} move the currently selected Band Times
entry up and down respectively.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_BANDTIMES_ATTRIBUTES" "Band Times Attributes"

The Band Times list lists the time ranges within the Time Band day
range when the Time Band is active. 

For example if the "Standard" Time Band lasts from 08:00 until 18:00
Monday to Friday then the Time Band entry for Standard will have "Mon"
and "Fri" as its days range and the entry "08:00-18:00" in its Band Times.

Note that the band starts at exactly 08:00 and actually finishes at
18:00, i.e. after the last second of 17:59.


The currently selected entry is edited using the @{i}From/To@{ui}
cycle and the @{i}Hours@{ui} and @{i}Mins@{ui} sliders. To edit the start of
the Band Time range, select "From" in the cycle and drag the sliders, and 
to edit the end of the range, select "To".

The times wrap round over midnight, so if a Band lasted from 18:00
until 08:00 the next day, you would simply enter 18:00-08:00 in the
list.

OnlineMeter takes account of both the Time Band day range and the Band
Times when deciding the current Time Band to select, so if a band
wraps over midnight then the Band is only valid at and after midnight
if the new day is also within the Time Band range.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_SETTINGPREFS" "Setting the Preferences"

@{b}Saving and Using@{ub}

Once you have created your Zones, Time Bands and Band Times, and
edited all the other whatsits to your requirements you can save the
settings in a variety of ways.


The @{i}Save@{ui} gadget saves the current settings to the OnlineMeter
standard preferences files: ENV:Online/Online.prefs and
ENVARC:Online/Online.prefs. These setting will then be used for the
current and subsequent sessions, even after a re-boot.

The @{i}Use@{ui} gadget saves the current settings to the OnlineMeter
current session preference file, ENV:Online/Online.prefs only. This will
cause the current and subsequent instances of OnlineMeter to use these
preferences, but the settings will be lost after a re-boot.

In both cases the ...:Online/ directory will be created if it does not
already exist. 


The @{i}Cancel @{ui} gadget forgets the current preferences and exits
OnlinePrefs. Please note that there is no "Are you Sure?" requester,
so be careful. The Close Window gadget performs the same operation.


In all cases the final result of selecting these gadgets is to exit
OnlinePrefs.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Save As... Menu Item" link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_SAVEAS"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENUS" "OnlinePrefs Menus"

The OnlinePrefs Menu bar looks like this:

   Project        Edit                  Settings
   @{"Open..." link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_OPEN"}       @{"Reset to Defaults" link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_RESET"}    @{"Create Icons" link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_CREATEICONS"}
   @{"Save As..." link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_SAVEAS"}    @{"Last Saved" link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_LASTSAVED"}
   ----------    @{"Restore" link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_RESTORE"}
   @{"About..." link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_ABOUT"}
   ----------
   @{"Quit" link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_QUIT"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_OPEN" "OnlinePrefs Project/Open..."

@{b}Open...@{ub} is used to load a preferences file from somewhere
other than the default locations. 

It brings up a file requester which is initially in the
SYS:Prefs/Presets drawer, but a preferences file may be loaded from
anywhere. Remember that you can drop preferences file icons onto the
ASL requester to set the path and/or file.

SEE ALSO

   OnlinePrefs Argument @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"}
   OnlineMeter Argument @{"PREFSFILE" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_PREFSFILE"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_RESET" "OnlinePrefs Edit/Reset to Defaults"

@{b}Reset to Defaults@{ub} resets all the @{"Global OnlineMeter settings" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALSETTINGS"} 
to their default values. All Zone information is deleted.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_CREATEICONS" "OnlinePrefs Settings/Create Icons"

The state of the @{b}Create Icons@{ub} menu item effects whether or
not icons are saved with files saved from the @{"Save As..." link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_SAVEAS"} menu.

If checked then the files will have an Project Icon saved with them with a
default tool of OnlinePrefs.

Icon files are never saved with the default preferences files 
(ENV:Online/Online.prefs and ENVARC:Online/Online.prefs) as created by
the Save and Use gadgets.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_SAVEAS" "OnlinePrefs Project/Save As..."

@{b}Save As...@{ub} brings up a file requester for saving the current
preferences to a file other than the default preferences files. The
requester initially opens in the SYS:Prefs/Presets drawer but files
can be saved anywhere.

SEE ALSO

   OnlinePrefs Argument @{"FROM" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_FROM"}
                        @{"ACTION" link "ONLINEPREFS_ARG_ACTION"}
   OnlineMeter Argument @{"PREFSFILE" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_PREFSFILE"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_LASTSAVED" "OnlinePrefs Edit/Last Saved"

@{b}Last Saved@{ub} restores the preferences from the last set of
preferences saved to ENVARC:Online/Online.prefs. 

Beware that there is no confirmation for the operation.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_RESTORE" "OnlinePrefs Edit/Restore"

@{b}Restore@{ub} restores the preferences from the last set of
preferences saved to ENV:Online/Online.prefs. 

Beware that there is no confirmation for the operation.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_ABOUT" "OnlinePrefs Project/About..."

@{b}About...@{ub} displays a requester with some brief information
about OnlinePrefs.

Always quote the version number from this requester if you have any
bug reports etc. to give the @{"Author" link "THE_AUTHOR"}.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_QUIT" "OnlinePrefs Project/Quit"

@{b}Quit@{ub} leaves OnlinePrefs. It has the same effect as the Cancel
and Close Window gadgets.

Beware that there is no confirmation for the operation.

@endnode



@node "ONLINEMETER" "OnlineMeter -- The Ultimate Call Coster"

@{b}OnlineMeter@{ub} is started from the Workbench by double clicking
on its icon, or from the CLI by typing its name. It can take several
@{"Arguments" link "ONLINEMETER_STARTUP"} which are used to override the preferences 
settings set by @{"OnlinePrefs" link "ONLINEPREFS"}.

Without any arguments (or ToolTypes) OnlineMeter loads the default
configuration file ENV:Online/Online.prefs (or ENVARC:Online/Online.prefs) 
and depending on those preferences opens its window accordingly.

NOW SEE

   @{"Startup" link "ONLINEMETER_STARTUP"}
   @{"Display" link "ONLINEMETER_DISPLAY"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_STARTUP" "OnlineMeter Startup"

OnlineMeter supports a number of arguments via either Icon ToolTypes
or CLI Arguments. The keywords are mostly the same in either case and
they follow standard (i.e. Style Guide compliant) Amiga conventions:

SYNOPSIS

   OnlineMeter
      @{"PREFSFILE/K," link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_PREFSFILE"}
      @{"LOG/S," link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOG"}
      @{"LOGFILE/K," link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOGFILE"}
      @{"PUBSCREEN/K," link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_PUBSCREEN"}
      @{"REXXNAME/K," link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_REXXNAME"}
      @{"SMALL/S," link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_SMALL"}
      @{"WARN/S," link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_WARN"}
      @{"ACCUMULATIVE/S," link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ACCUMULATIVE"}
      @{"TOP/N/K, LEFT/N/K" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_TOPLEFT"}
      @{"VARS/S" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_VARS"}
      @{"POPKEY/K" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_POPKEY"}
      @{"STARTKEY/K" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STARTKEY"}
      @{"STOPKEY/K" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STOPKEY"}
      @{"ABORTKEY/K" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ABORTKEY"}
      @{"CDITY/K" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_CDITY"}
      @{"BEEPONWARN/S" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_BEEPONWARN"}
      @{"COMMENT/K" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_COMMENT"}

In case you are not familiar with CLI templates, /K means that the
keyword must be specified for the argument to take effect (i.e. you
cannot rely on the order of the arguments alone), /S means that the
argument is a boolean switch, and /N means that the argument is
expected to be an integer.

Most of these settings can be set via the preferences file using
@{"OnlinePrefs" link "ONLINEPREFS"}; if they are given as an Argument (or ToolType)
then they override the setting in the preferences file. 

The only exceptions are PREFSFILE, since OnlineMeter tries to read
ENV:Online/Online.prefs by default, and TOP and LEFT, since these are
immediate operators.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_PREFSFILE" "PREFSFILE"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  PREFSFILE=<preferences file name>
   CLI Argument  -  PREFSFILE <preferences file name>

FUNCTION

   Causes OnlineMeter to load its preferences from the given file instead of
   from the default preferences file (ENV:Online/Online.prefs etc.).

   The file is loaded before any other arguments are applied so that they
   can correctly override these preferences if desired.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Save As..." link "ONLINEPREFS_MENU_SAVEAS"} OnlinePrefs Menu Item.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOG" "LOG"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  LOG=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument  -  LOG or NOLOG

FUNCTION

   Enables or Disables Call Information Logging.

SEE ALSO

   @{"LOGFILE" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOGFILE"}
   @{"OnlinePrefs Log Checkbox"  link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOG"}
   @{"Log Menu Item" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_LOG"}
   @{"Logging Calls" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOGFILE" "LOGFILE"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  LOGFILE=<log file name>
   CLI Argument  -  LOGFILE <log file name>

FUNCTION

   Specifies the name of the file to use for logging call information.

   Logging only takes place if enabled.

SEE ALSO

   @{"LOG" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOG"}
   @{"OnlinePrefs Log File string" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOGFILE"}
   @{"Call Logging" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_VARS" "VARS"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  -  VARS=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument -  VARS or NOVARS

FUNCTION

   Controls writing of Environmental variables ONLINECOST and 
   ONLINEDURATION when Logging is enabled.

SEE ALSO

   @{"NOSAVE" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_QUIT"} option in QUIT ARexx Command.
   @{"Logging Environmental Variables" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG_VARS"}
   @{"LOG" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOG"}
   @{"LOGFILE" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOGFILE"}
   @{"OnlinePrefs Log Checkbox"  link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOG"}
   @{"OnlinePrefs Vars Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_VARS"}
   @{"Log Menu Item" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_LOG"}
   @{"Logging Calls" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_PUBSCREEN" "PUBSCREEN"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  PUBSCREEN=<public screen name>
   CLI Argument  -  PUBSCREEN <public screen name>

FUNCTION

   Specifies the name of the Public Screen to open the OnlineMeter window.

   If the Public Screen does not exist then OnlineMeter opens on the
   default Public Screen, usually Workbench.

SEE ALSO

   @{"OnlinePrefs Screen string" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_PUBSCREEN"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_REXXNAME" "REXXNAME"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  REXXNAME=<rexx port name>
   CLI Argument  -  REXXNAME <rexx port name>

FUNCTION

   Specifies the basename for the OnlineMeter ARexx port.

SEE ALSO

   @{"OnlinePrefs Rexx Name string" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_REXXNAME"}
   @{"OnlineMeter ARexx" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_SMALL" "SMALL"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  SMALL=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument  -  SMALL or NOSMALL

FUNCTION

   Controls whether OnlineMeter opens a small undetailed or a large 
   detailed window.


SEE ALSO

   @{"OnlinePrefs Small Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_OPENSMALL"}
   @{"Display" link "ONLINEMETER_DISPLAY"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_HIDDEN" "HIDDEN"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  - CX_POPUP=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument - HIDDEN or NOHIDDEN

FUNCTION

   Controls whether or not OnlineMeter opens its window on startup.
   
SEE ALSO
   @{"OnlinePrefs Hidden Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_OPENHIDDEN"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_WARN" "WARN"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  WARN=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument  -  WARN or NOWARN

FUNCTION

   Controls whether or not OnlineMeter should warn the user when a @{"Time Band" link "TERMINOLOGY" 14}
   is about to end.

   If enabled OnlineMeter will post a requester 3 minutes before the end of
   the current Band.

SEE ALSO

   @{"OnlinePrefs Warn Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_WARN"}
   @{"Warn Menu Item" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_WARNING"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_BEEPONWARN" "BEEPONWARN"

SYNOPSIS 
   
   WB ToolType   -   BEEPONWARN=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument  -   BEEPONWARN or NOBEEPONWARN
                 or  BEEP or NOBEEP
FUNCTION

   Controls whether OnlineMeter beeps the display when a End of Band 
   Warning requester is posted.

SEE ALSO
   @{"OnlinePrefs Beep Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_BEEP"}
   @{"WARN" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_WARN"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ACCUMULATIVE" "ACCUMULATIVE"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType   -  ACCUMULATIVE=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument  -  ACCUMULATIVE or NOACCUMULATIVE

FUNCTION

   Enables or Disables display of Total Cost and Duration for the current
   session as opposed to display of only Current Call Duration and Cost.

SEE ALSO

   @{"OnlinePrefs Accumulative Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_ACCUMULATIVE"}
   @{"Accumulative Menu Item" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ACCUMULATIVE"}

@endnode 

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_TOPLEFT" "TOP, LEFT"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  -  LEFT=<Window x Position> TOP=<Window y Position>
   CLI Argument -  LEFT <Window x Position> TOP <Window y Position>
	        or X    <Window x Position> Y   <Window y Position>
   
FUNCTION

   Sets the opening position for the OnlineMeter window. Out of range
   values will be limited as per Intuition rules.

   Either or both co-ordinates may be specified.

SEE ALSO

   @{"SMALL" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_SMALL"}

@endnode

@node ONLINEMETER_ARG_POPKEY "POPKEY"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  -  CX_POPKEY=<cx key sequence>
   CLI Argument -  POPKEY <cx key sequence>

FUNCTION
   
   Sets the OnlineMeter Show hotkey.

SEE ALSO
   @{"OnlineMeter Hotkeys" link "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS"}
   @{"STARTKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STARTKEY"}
   @{"STOPKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STOPKEY"}
   @{"ABORTKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ABORTKEY"}
   @{"CDITY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_CDITY"}

@endnode

@node ONLINEMETER_ARG_STARTKEY "STARTKEY"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  -  STARTKEY=<cx key sequence>
   CLI Argument -  STARTKEY <cx key sequence>

FUNCTION
   
   Sets the OnlineMeter Start hotkey.

SEE ALSO
   @{"OnlineMeter Hotkeys" link "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS"}
   @{"POPKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_POPKEY"}
   @{"STOPKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STOPKEY"}
   @{"ABORTKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ABORTKEY"}
   @{"CDITY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_CDITY"}

@endnode

@node ONLINEMETER_ARG_STOPKEY "STOPKEY"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  -  STOPKEY=<cx key sequence>
   CLI Argument -  STOPKEY <cx key sequence>

FUNCTION
   
   Sets the OnlineMeter Stop hotkey.

SEE ALSO
   @{"OnlineMeter Hotkeys" link "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS"}
   @{"POPKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_POPKEY"}
   @{"STARTKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STARTKEY"}
   @{"ABORTKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ABORTKEY"}
   @{"CDITY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_CDITY"}

@endnode

@node ONLINEMETER_ARG_ABORTKEY "ABORTKEY"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  -  ABORTKEY=<cx key sequence>
   CLI Argument -  ABORTKEY <cx key sequence>

FUNCTION
   
   Sets the OnlineMeter Abort hotkey.

SEE ALSO
   @{"OnlineMeter Hotkeys" link "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS"}
   @{"POPKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_POPKEY"}
   @{"STARTKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STARTKEY"}
   @{"STOPKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STOPKEY"}
   @{"CDITY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_CDITY"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_CDITY" "CDITY"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  -  CDITY=<YES or NO>
   CLI Argument -  CDITY or NOCDITY

FUNCTION

   Enables or Disables the OnlineMeter Commodities exchange interface.

SEE ALSO
   @{"OnlineMeter Hotkeys" link "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS"}
   @{"POPKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_POPKEY"}
   @{"STARTKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STARTKEY"}
   @{"STOPKEY" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_STOPKEY"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_ARG_COMMENT" "COMMENT"

SYNOPSIS

   WB ToolType  - COMMENT=<Comment String>
   CLI Argument - COMMENT <Comment String>

FUNCTION

   Sets the Comment which is saved with all Log-File entries.

   Only the first 20 characters are significant.

SEE ALSO
   @{"Log File" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG_FILE"}
   @{"SETCOMMENT ARexx Command" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_SETCOMMENT"}

@endnode



@node "ONLINEMETER_DISPLAY" "The OnlineMeter Display"

@{b}OnlineMeter@{ub} has two modes of display, Normal and Small. The
Zoom gadget in the Top-Right hand corner controls the size, as do the
@{"OnlinePrefs settings" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_OPENSMALL"} and the @{"OnlineMeter ToolTypes" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_SMALL"}.

In Normal mode it displays the Current (or @{"Accumulative" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ACCUMULATIVE"}) call Cost and
Duration, and the currently selected Zone, and provides call control
@{"Gadgets" link "ONLINEMETER_GADGETS"}.

In Small mode the OnlineMeter window is `Zoomed' to the height of a
window title-bar, and the display alternates between showing the Cost
and the Duration of the call.

In both modes OnlineMeter's @{"Menus" link "ONLINEMETER_MENUS"} can be accessed.

SEE ALSO

   @{"OnlinePrefs" link "ONLINEPREFS_ZONE_ATTRIBUTES"}.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_GADGETS" "OnlineMeter Front Panel Gadgets"

OnlineMeter provides the basic manual control function as front panel
gadgets:


@{i}Start @{ui}starts costing a call, using the cost information of
the currently selected Zone. Pressing Start whilst a call is already
in progress will terminate the call, performing any rounding necessary
and making a @{"Log" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"} entry if 
@{"enabled" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOG"}, 
before immediately starting to cost the next call. The Start button
causes the @{"minimum charge" link "TERMINOLOGY_MINIMUM_CHARGE"} or
@{"Unit" link "TERMINOLOGY_UNIT"} cost to be added to the call cost
immediately.

@{i}Stop@{ui} finishes a call in progress and makes a Log entry if
Logging is enabled.

Pressing @{i}Reset @{ui}once resets the cost and duration of the
current call to zero, but continues costing the call from that moment
if OnlineMeter's timer is running. Double-Clicking on Reset resets the
cost and duration of the current call @{i}and @{ui}the accumulated total. 
Both function will effect any @{"logging information" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"} saved; 
be especially careful with the Double-Click function.

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS" "OnlineMeter Hotkeys"

OnlineMeter now installs as a Commodity and it's essential features
can be controlled by Hotkeys.

OnlineMeter therefore appears in Commodities Exchange utilities and
can be Hidden/Shown, and Removed using the Commodites exchange
facilities. The Enable/Disable control does not effect OnlineMeter
itself but just it's hotkeys.

Hotkeys exist for Showing the OnlineMeter interface if it is Hidden
(or you can't find it!), and Starting, Stopping and Aborting the
Meter. 

The Hotkey definitions are fully configurable using OnlinePrefs or
through OnlineMeter Arguments/ToolTypes.

Hotkey strings, use the standard Commodities specifiers, i.e.:

 · (l|r|%)shift, (l|r|%)amiga , (l|r|%)alt, control|cntl, 
 · f1..f10
 · numpad
 · esc, backspace, enter, home, insert etc.
 · alphanumeric keys 

For example, to map a command to right-shift+control+. on the numeric
keypad, you would use the string:

	rshift control numpad .

If you find a sequence doesn't work, it's probably because some other
program has already used it: I'm afraid it's up to you to find out which!


SEE ALSO

   @{"Hotkeys Preferences" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_HOTKEYS"}
   @{"Hotkeys Arguments" link "ONLINEMETER_STARTUP"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_MENUS" "OnlineMeter Menus"

The OnlineMeter Menu Bar looks like this:

   Project     Meter        Preferences     Zones
   @{"About..." link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ABOUT"}   @{"Reset" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_RESET"}       @{"Accumulative" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ACCUMULATIVE"}   @{"Zone List" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ZONE_LIST"}
   --------    @{"Reset All" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_RESETALL"}   @{"Warning" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_WARNING"}
   @{"Hide" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_HIDE"}       @{"Abort" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ABORT"}       @{"Log" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_LOG"}
   @{"Jump" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_JUMP"}       ------------
   @{"Quit" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_QUIT"}       @{"Information..." link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_INFORMATION"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ABOUT" "OnlineMeter Project/About..."


@{b}About...@{ub} displays a requester with some brief information
about OnlineMeter. It is displayed asynchronously with OnlineMeter's
operation.

Always quote the version number from this requester if you have any
bug reports etc. to give the @{"Author" link "THE_AUTHOR"}.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_RESET" "OnlineMeter Meter/Reset"

@{b}Reset@{ub} resets the cost and duration of the current call to zero.
It has the same effect as pressing the @{"Reset Gadget" link "ONLINEMETER_GADGETS" 16} on the front
panel.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Reset Gadget" link "ONLINEMETER_GADGETS" 16}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ACCUMULATIVE" "OnlineMeter Preferences/Accumulative"

@{b}Accumulative@{ub} controls whether OnlineMeter displays the total
Accumulative cost and duration of all calls made in a session, or just
the cost and duration of the current call.

SEE ALSO

   @{"ACCUMULATIVE OnlineMeter Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ACCUMULATIVE"}
   @{"Accumulative OnlinePrefs Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_ACCUMULATIVE"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ZONE_LIST" "OnlineMeter Zones"

The @{b}Zone Menu@{ub} lists up to 32 Zones for selection of the
current Zone for charging information.

SEE ALSO

   @{"OnlinePrefs Zone Creation" link "ONLINEPREFS_ZONES"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_RESETALL" "OnlineMeter Meter/Reset All"

@{b}Reset All@{ub} resets both the cost and duration of the current
call, and of the Accumulated calls this session to zero. It has the same 
effect as Double-Clicking the @{"Reset Gadget" link "ONLINEMETER_GADGETS" 16} on the front panel.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Reset Gadget" link "ONLINEMETER_GADGETS" 16}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ABORT" "OnlineMeter Meter/Abort"

@{b}Abort@{ub} terminates and cancels the current call, as if it had never
been, made. No Logging is performed and the meter is left in a Stopped 
state.

This is very useful if you have set Online-o-Meter up with in a script
and fail to connect to the remote modem, for example if it is engaged.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_WARNING" "OnlineMeter Preferences/Warning"

The @{b}Warning@{ub} menu item controls whether or not OnlineMeter
displays a requester warning of an approaching Time Band end. If
checked a warning is generated 3 minutes before the band ends.

SEE ALSO

   @{"WARN OnlineMeter Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_WARN"}
   @{"Warn OnlinePrefs Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_WARN"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_HIDE" "OnlineMeter Project/Hide"

@{b}Hide@{ub} closes the OnlineMeter window, but leaves OnlineMeter running 
in the background. 

While in this state OnlineMeter can be controlled by @{"ARexx" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX"} and 
its @{"Hotkeys" link "ONLINEMETER_HOTKEYS"}.  OnlineMeter will open its window when it receives 
a @{"SETWINDOW SHOW" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_SETWINDOW"} command from ARexx, or if you press the POPKEY 
hotkey or select Show on a Commodities Exchange program, or if you send 
OnlineMeter a Control-F break signal via the Shell @{i}Break@{ui} command or a 
System Monitor utility such as @{i}ARTM@{ui}.

SEE ALSO

   @{"ARexx" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_LOG" "OnlineMeter Preferences/Log"

The @{b}Log@{ub} Menu Item controls whether @{"Logging" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"} is enabled or not. 

SEE ALSO

   @{"LOG OnlineMeter Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOG"}
   @{"Log OnlinePrefs Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOG"}
   @{"Logging" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_JUMP" "OnlineMeter Project/Jump"

The @{b}Jump@{ub} Menu Item causes OnlineMeter to close its window and
attempt to open on the next Public Screen it can find using the
NextPubScreen() intuition function.

Continually selecting this option will make OnlineMeter move across
all public screens currently open; if only Workbench is open,
OnlineMeter will reopen there.

The size of the window will be maintained across jumps.

SEE ALSO

   @{"PubScreen Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_PUBSCREEN"}
   @{"PubScreen Attribute" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_PUBSCREEN"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_INFORMATION" "OnlineMeter Meter/Information..."

The @{b}Information...@{ub} Menu Item pops up a requester telling you
information about the Current and the Next Time Bands. 

The requester tells you the state of the meter (RUNNING or STOPPED),
the current Band's name, how it is charged, and when it ends, and name
and information for the Band which will become active after the
current one. In addition, if the meter is running, it tells you at
which time the current call was started.

A typical display might look like this:

	Meter is RUNNING.
	Started Sunday 18/06/95 18:49:11
	Current Band is `Weekend' at 90.00 Seconds per Unit
	Band ends Monday 19/06/95 00:00
	Next Band is `Economy' at 50.35 Seconds per Unit


@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_MENU_QUIT" "OnlineMeter Project/Quit"

The @{b}Quit@{ub} Menu Item leaves OnlineMeter, terminating any calls
in progress and saving the Accumulative Totals to the @{"logging variables" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}
if this functionality is enabled.

The Window Close Gadget has the same effect, as does the @{"QUIT" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_QUIT"} ARexx 
command and sending OnlineMeter a Control-C via the CLI @{i}break @{ui}
command or a System Monitor utility.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Logging" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}

@endnode


@node "ONLINEMETER_LOG" "Call Logging"

Probably the most important and useful feature of OnlineMeter is its ability
to generate log information for all the calls it has costed. This enables
you to keep track of all the calls you have made and to predict what your
next phone bill will be.

Log information consists of two parts:

   @{"The Log File" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG_FILE"} and the @{"Logging Environmental Variables" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG_VARS"}.


SEE ALSO
   OnlineMeter
    @{"LOG Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOG"}
    @{"LOGFILE Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_LOGFILE"}
    @{"VARS Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_VARS"}
    @{"Log Menu Item" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_LOG"}

   OnlinePrefs
    @{"Log Enabled Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOG"}
    @{"Log Vars Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_VARS"}
    @{"Log File string" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOGFILE"}

@endnode 



@node "ONLINEMETER_LOG_FILE" "The OnlineMeter Log File"

The @{b}Log File@{ub} contains an entry for each call OnlineMeter has costed;
each entry consists of a line in the following format:

   
   <Zone Name><Comment><Date><Time><Duration><Cost>
   
e.g.
   
National B1          0813173333           06-Jul-94 17:32:25 00:42:38    72.1
Local                Mum                  07-Jul-94 09:11:55 00:03:57     4.2
<- 20 characters  -> <- 20 characters  ->


The log entry is created at the end of each call (if Logging is enabled), 
signified either by Stopping OnlineMeter's timer or Starting another call.

The file will grow to fill all available space, so I suggest you purge
the last quarters bill when you pay it!!

The <Comment> field may be set using the @{"SETCOMMENT" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_SETCOMMENT"} ARexx command,
or by stating it with an ARexx @{"START" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_START"} command. It can be set initially using 
the @{"COMMENT" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_COMMENT"} OnlineMeter Argument.

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_LOG_VARS" "OnlineMeter Log Environmental Variables"

The environmental variables @{b}Online/ONLINECOST@{ub} and @{b}Online/ONLINEDURATION@{ub} 
keep track of the total costs of all calls made, depending on whether
Call Logging and Variable saving is enabled at exit time. They have
the same format as the OnlineMeter display i.e. uu.ff and hh:mm:ss.

Every time OnlineMeter is exited (and var logging is enabled) the
internal Accumulated Cost and Duration values are added to these
variables, therefore for them to be accurate (and thus useful) beware
of using the Reset facility and of switching the machine off without
quitting OnlineMeter. The variables are saved to both ENV: and ENVARC:
so they survive a re-boot.

Their values can be read and set using the CLI commands e.g.
@{i}

   getenv Online/ONLINECOST 
   getenv Online/ONLINEDURATION 

   setenv Online/ONLINECOST 342.00 
   setenv Online/ONLINEDURATION 00:00:00 

@{ui}

SEE ALSO
	@{"GETCOST ARexx Command" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETCOST"}
	@{"Log Attribute" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_LOG"}
        @{"Vars Attribute" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_VARS"}
        @{"VARS Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_VARS"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_AREXX" "External Control through ARexx"

@{b}OnlineMeter@{ub} has the ability to be controlled by ARexx making 
interfacing with most Communications packages easy.

The default ARexx port name is "OnlineREXX" although this can be changed 
via @{"Preferences" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_REXXNAME"} and OnlineMeter @{"Arguments" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_REXXNAME"}.

OnlineMeter provides the following commands:

	@{"ABORT" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_ABORT"}
	@{"ACCUMULATIVE" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_ACCUMULATIVE"}
	@{"GETCOST" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETCOST"}
	@{"LOG" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_LOG"}
	@{"LOGFILE" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_LOGFILE"}
	@{"QUIT" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_QUIT"}
	@{"READPREFS" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_READPREFS"}
	@{"RESET" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_RESET"}
	@{"SETCOMMENT" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_SETCOMMENT"}
	@{"SETWINDOW" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_SETWINDOW"}
	@{"SETZONE" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_SETZONE"}
	@{"START" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_START"}
	@{"STOP" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_STOP"}
	@{"WARN" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_WARN"}


The syntax matches that used for CLI ReadArgs() arguments:


	/S  -  Switch argument. e.g. ON and OFF

	/N  -  Numerical (integer) argument.

        /A  -  Required i.e. argument must be specified for command
               to work.

	/F  -  Argument includes rest of line including spaces.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Getting Results" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETTING_RESULTS"}

@endnode

@node ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETTING_RESULTS "Getting Results from ARexx Commands"

Some OnlineMeter ARexx commands return results which can be used by the
calling program.

Results can be passed back in two ways:

   · As a variable string with multiple arguments separated by spaces.
   · As a structured variable with each argument making up a field.


@{b}IMPORTANT@{ub} Remember to specify `OPTIONS RESULTS' in your ARexx script
when expecting results or you will see nothing!


For example GETCOST COST, DURATION :

@{i}
   OPTIONS RESULTS
   GETCOST VAR MyCost 
   SAY 'MyCost =' MyCost 
@{ui}

gives:

   MyCost = 0.00 00:00:00

whereas:

@{i}
   OPTIONS RESULTS
   GETCOST STEM MyCost.
   SAY 'Cost =' MyCost.cost
   SAY 'Duration =' MyCost.duration
@{ui}

@{b}IMPORTANT@{ub} The `.' after the variable name is required!

gives:

   Cost = 0.00
   Duration = 00:00:00
   

STEM is probably the more useful of the two.

@endnode


@rem ---------------------------ARexx Commands------------------------------

@node "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_ABORT" "ABORT"

SYNOPSIS

   ABORT

FUNCTION

   Aborts the current call, Stopping OnlineMeter and not making a Log Entry
   or adding the call information to the Accumulated call data.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Abort" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ABORT"} Menu Item.
   @{"Logging" link "ONLINEMETER_LOG"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_ACCUMULATIVE" "ACCUMULATIVE"

SYNOPSIS

   ACCUMULATIVE ON/S,OFF/S

FUNCTION

   Changes the Accumulative display setting.

SEE ALSO

   @{"ACCUMULATIVE Argument" link "ONLINEMETER_ARG_ACCUMULATIVE"}
   @{"Accumulative Menu Item" link "ONLINEMETER_MENU_ACCUMULATIVE"}
   @{"OnlinePrefs Accumulative Checkbox" link "ONLINEPREFS_GLOBALS_ACCUMULATIVE"}

@endnode

@node "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETCOST" "GETCOST"

SYNOPSIS

   GETCOST ACCUMULATIVE/S

RESULTS

   COST, DURATION

FUNCTION

   Returns the current cost and duration from OnlineMeter. 

   If the ACCUMULATIVE argument is given returns the Accumulated rather than
   the Current Call cost. If a call is in progress this is the sum of the
   two.

SEE ALSO

   @{"Getting Results" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETTING_RESULTS"}
   @{"Display" link "ONLINEMETER_DISPLAY"}
   
@endnode

@rem @node "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETCURRZONEINFO" "GETCURRENTZONEINFO"
@rem 
@rem SYNOPSIS
@rem 
@rem    GETCURRENTZONEINFO
@rem 
@rem RESULTS
@rem 
@rem    ZONENAME, BANDNAME, MINCHARGE, BILLINGPERIOD, ROUNDING, COSTMIN,
@rem    ENDDAY/N, ENDMONTH/N, ENDYEAR/N, ENDHOUR/N, ENDMINUTE/N, 
@rem    TIMELEFTHOURS, TIMELEFTMINS, TIMELEFTSECS
@rem 
@rem FUNCTION
@rem 
@rem    Returns volumous information about the currently selected Zone and
@rem    current Time Band.
@rem 
@rem SEE ALSO
@rem 
@rem    @{"Getting Results" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETTING_RESULTS"}
@rem 
@rem @endnode
@rem 
@rem @node "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETZBANDS" "GETZBANDS"
@rem 
@rem SYNOPSIS
@rem 
@rem    GETZBANDS ZONE/A/F
@rem 
@rem RESULTS
@rem 
@rem    NAMES/M
@rem 
@rem FUNCTION
@rem 
@rem    Returns the names of the Time Bands for the specified Zone.
@rem 
@rem SEE ALSO
@rem 
@rem    @{"Getting Results" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETTING_RESULTS"}
@rem 
@rem @endnode
@rem 
@rem @node "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETZBDAYS" "GETZBDAYS"
@rem 
@rem SYNOPSIS
@rem 
@rem    GETZBDAYS ZONE/A BAND/A
@rem 
@rem RESULTS
@rem 
@rem    DAYS/M
@rem 
@rem FUNCTION
@rem 
@rem    Returns the names of the days when a particular Time Band is valid for
@rem    a Zone.
@rem 
@rem SEE ALSO
@rem 
@rem    @{"Getting Results" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETTING_RESULTS"}
@rem 
@rem @endnode
@rem 
@rem @node "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETZBTIMES" "GETZBTIMES"
@rem 
@rem SYNOPSIS
@rem 
@rem    GETZBTIMES ZONE/A BAND/A
@rem 
@rem RESULTS
@rem 
@rem    TIMESFROM/M, TIMESTO/M
@rem 
@rem FUNCTION
@rem 
@rem    Returns the times when a Time Band is valid for a zone.
@rem 
@rem    The results are paired in order e.g. TIMESFROM.1 goes with TIMESTO.1
@rem 
@rem BUGS
@rem 
@rem    The results only make sense with the STEM keyword.
@rem 
@rem SEE ALSO
@rem 
@rem    @{"Getting Results" link "ONLINEMETER_AREXX_GETTING_RESULTS"}
